 where the Ottoman Empire dominated former Byzantium territories and offered shelter for battered Conversos (converted Jews). The text recounting the last fifteen years of Gracia's life at the center of the Empire is particularly revealing. Birnbaum's biography has the unique distinction of being the first among many studies to pay tribute to a woman during this period. It is also one of the first titles to pay equal attention to the lives of the Conversos in Christian West Europe and in the Muslim East.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aCrypto-JewszIberian PeninsulavBiography. 0aJewish womenzPortugalvBiography. 0aJewszEuropexEconomic conditionsy16th century. 0aJewszEuropexSocial conditionsy16th century. 0aJewszPortugalvBiography. 0aSephardimzPortugalvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Women.2bisacsh  aBiography, Constantinople, Economic conditions, Jewish women, Jews, Ottoman Empire, Sephardim.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998z978311078055040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978615521123240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9786155211232423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9786155211232/original  a978-3-11-078055-0  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998c1998d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK